en: The History of the most Renowned Don Quixote of Mancha: And his Trusty Squire, Sancho Pancha [sic], Now made English according to the Humor of our Modern Language by J.P.
The adventure of the Enchanted Head

Don Antonio Moreno shows the enchanted head to don Quixote and Sancho; don Antonio's wife and friends also appear.The head as a Roman bust, accurate to Cervantes' text.Episode first represented by Bouttats (Amberes: Verdussen, 1672 - 1673), whose composition is copied here in part.

1 - Wrongly-placed as a frontispiece. It should be f.p. 533 (Part II, Book IV).2 - In same folio with "Don Quixot conquer'd by the Knight of the White Moon".3 - In Cushing's copy, the first plate of this edition ("Don Quixot Dubb'd a knight Errant by the Innkeeper" and "Don Quixot's Encounter with the Windmills") is wanting. This missing plate should appear f.p. 29 (Part I, Book I).

Frontispiece with well-known iconography.In the foreground, don Quixote with the barber basin and Rocinante and Sancho, as a jester, with his donkey.In the background, Dulcinea feeding the pigs.Well-detailed image (landscape, rural English architectures...) in keeping with a humorous English reading of the novel.
1 - In Cushing's copy, this frontispiece is a facsimile reproduction of the original burin engraving.

Don Quixot and the Carrier fighting for the Innkeeper's Maid

In the foreground, don Quixote lying on the broken bed.In the background, the fighting among Sancho, Maritornes and the muleteer is discovered by the innkeeper, who holds a candle.Composition based on Savery's illustration (Dordrecht: Savery, 1657).
1 - Indication "P. 35" appears into the illustration, but the textual reference to this illustration is in p. 66 (Part I, Book III, Chapter II).

Don Quixot's encounter with the Flock of sheep
18.1 Adventure of the flock of sheep (rebaños)

Two different scenes are included in the same illustration:In the foreground, don Quixote attacks a flock of sheep, while several shepherds stone him.In the background, the consequences of the adventure: don Quixote, defeated, is helped by Sancho, while the shepherds gather the sheep and pick up the dead ones.Drawing and engraving are acceptable, but poor.
1 - The illustration includes the indication "Page 60", but the textual reference appears in Part I, Book III, Chapter IV, p. 75.2 - This is the first individual representation of this adventure.

43.2 Maritornes and innkeeper’s daughter hang DQ from window by a hand

Don Quixote falls from Rocinante and remains hanged and tied by his hand to an inn window when four travelers (servants of don Luis' father) arrive to the inn.The innkeeper appears to discover who is crying.Maritornes is ready to untie don Quixote, but the innkeeper's daughter should not appear in the window too.Composition based on Bouttats' (Amberes: Verdussen, 1672 - 1673), but turned.Drawing and engraving are poor.
1 - Indication "Page 243" given in the illustration, but the textual reference appears in Part I, Book IV, Chapter XVI, p. 238.
